18 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
19 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
20 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3-412 of Title 2, unless there
21 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
22 A. The Oklahoma Department of Agriculture, Food, and Forestry
23 shall administer the Oklahoma Industrial Hemp Program in full
24
Req. No. 17299 Page 1

1 conf ormity with the definition of hemp in 7 U.S.C., Section 1639o,
2 as amended by Section 781 of Public Law 119-37.
3 B. No license, permit, or authorization issued under this
4 program shall allow the production, processing, sale, or
5 distribution of any product that is excluded from the definition of
6 hemp under federal law, except as expressly exempted by state law in
7 Section 3-402 of this title.
8 C. The Department may promulgate rules to implement testing
9 protocols for total tetrahydrocannabinol (THC), container limits,
10 age verification, point-of-sale restrictions, labeling, packaging,
11 and exclusions for synthetic or non-naturally occurring
12 cannabinoids.
13 D. Any state agency that issues a license, permit, or other
14 authorization to any entity subject to the provisions of this act,
15 including but not limited to the Department and the Alcoholic
16 Beverage Laws Enforcement (ABLE) Commission, shall have the
17 authority to revoke or suspend such license, permit, or
18 authorization upon a finding that the licensee or permittee has
19 violated any provision of this act or rules promulgated pursuant
20 thereto. In addition to revocation or suspension, the agency shall
21 impose a civil fine of not less than Ten Thousand Dollars
22 ($10,000.00) for each violation.
23 E. Any product that does not qualify as hemp under this
24 section, and is not exempted under state law, shall be subject to
Req. No. 17299 Page 2

1 the provisions of the Uniform Controlled Dangerous Substances Act,
2 Section 2-101 et seq., of Title 63 of the Oklahoma Statutes.
3 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 2 O.S. 2021, Section 3-402, as
4 last amended by Section 1, Chapter 266, O.S.L. 2024 (2 O.S. Supp.
5 2025, Section 3-402), is amended to read as follows:
6 Section 3-402. As used in the Oklahoma Industrial Hemp Program:
7 1. “Container” means the innermost wrapping, packaging, or
8 vessel in direct contact with a final hemp-derived cannabinoid
9 product in which the final product is enclosed for retail sale to
10 consumers, such as a jar, bottle, bag, box, can, carton, or
11 cartridge;
12 2. “Department” means the Oklahoma Department of Agriculture,
13 Food, and Forestry;
14 2. 3. “Fiber” means the stalk of the industrial hemp plant and
15 does not include the flower or seeds of the plant;
16 3. 4. “Flower” means the part of the industrial hemp plant that
17 contains the majority of the industrial hemp plant’s
18 tetrahydrocannabinol and other cannabinoids;
19 4. 5. “Grain” means all of the parts of an industrial hemp
20 plant except the stalk or the flower of the industrial hemp plant;
21 6. “Final hemp-derived cannabinoid product” means any
22 intermediate or final product derived from hemp, other than
23 industrial hemp, that contains cannabinoids in any form and is
24
Req. No. 17299 Page 3

1 inte nded for human or animal use through ingestion, inhalation,
2 topical application, or other form of administration;
3 5. 7. “Handling” means possessing or storing industrial hemp
4 for any period of time on premises owned, operated or controlled by
5 a person licensed to cultivate or process industrial hemp and also
6 includes possessing or storing industrial hemp in a vehicle for any
7 period of time other than during its actual transport from the
8 premises of a licensed person to cultivate or process industrial
9 hemp to the premises of another licensed person;
10 6. 8. “Industrial hemp” or "hemp" means the plant Cannabis
11 sativa L. and any part of the plant, including the seeds thereof,
12 and all derivatives, extracts, cannabinoids, isomers, acids, salts
13 and salts of isomers, whether growing or not, with a total delta-9
14 tetrahydrocannabinol concentration of not more than three-tenths of
15 one percent (0.3%) on a dry-weight basis, as defined in 7 U.S.C.,
16 Section 1639o, as amended by Section 781 of Public Law 119-37.
17 Furthermore, industrial hemp means hemp that is grown for the use of
18 the stalk, whole grain, oil, cake, nut, hull, or any other
19 noncannabinoid derivative of the seeds, or for fiber, or for
20 immature plants, such as microgreens or other edible leaf products,
21 or for research purposes by an institution of higher education that
22 does not enter the stream of commerce.
23 The term "hemp" does not include:
24
Req. No. 17299 Page 4

1 a. viable seeds from a cannabis plant that exceed a total
2 tetrahydrocannabinols concentration, including
3 tetrahydrocannabinolic acid, of three-tenths of one
4 percent (0.3%) on a dry-weight basis,
5 b. any cannabinoid that is synthesized or manufactured
6 outside the plant Cannabis sativa L. or that is not
7 capable of being naturally produced by the plant,
8 c. intermediate hemp-derived cannabinoid products that
9 contain greater than three-tenths of one percent
10 (0.3%) total tetrahydrocannabinols concentration,
11 including tetrahydrocannabinolic acid, on a dry-weight
12 basis or that contain any cannabinoid described in
13 subparagraph b of this paragraph, or
14 d. final hemp-derived cannabinoid products containing
15 greater than four-tenths milligram (0.4 mg) combined
16 total per container of total tetrahydrocannabinols,
17 including tetrahydrocannabinolic acid, and any other
18 cannabinoids that have similar effects, or are
19 marketed to have similar effects, on humans or animals
20 as tetrahydrocannabinol, as determined by the United
21 States Secretary of Health and Human Services.
22 Provided, however, that the exclusion in subparagraph d of this
23 paragraph shall not apply to hemp-derived cannabinoid beverages
24 containing ten milligrams (10 mg) or less of total
Req. No. 17299 Page 5

1 tetr ahydrocannabinols per container that are sold exclusively to
2 persons twenty-one (21) years of age or older in a package store
3 licensed under the Oklahoma Alcoholic Beverage Control Act, Title
4 37A of the Oklahoma Statutes. Such beverages shall be subject to
5 age verification, labeling, packaging, testing, and other
6 requirements established by the Department in consultation with the
7 Alcoholic Beverage Laws Enforcement (ABLE) Commission;
8 7. 9. “Key participant” means a person who has a direct or
9 indirect financial interest in the entity producing hemp, such as an
10 owner or partner in a partnership. A key participant includes an
11 individual who is part of a corporate entity or a tribal-owned
12 corporation. A key participant also includes an executive-level
13 individual such as a chief executive officer, chief operating
14 officer, or chief financial officer. Such term shall not include
15 such management personnel as a farm, field, or shift manager or a
16 member of the leadership of a tribal government who is acting in his
17 or her capacity as a tribal leader except when such member exercises
18 executive managerial control over hemp production;
19 8. 10. “Licensee” means a person who holds a valid Industrial
20 Hemp License to grow industrial hemp under the Oklahoma Industrial
21 Hemp Program. A licensee shall have the ability to remediate
22 noncompliant industrial hemp with a total delta-9
23 tetrahydrocannabinol concentration of not more than one percent
24 (1.0%) on a dry-weight basis for retesting as set forth by the
Req. No. 17299 Page 6

1 Depa rtment as long as the noncompliant industrial hemp has a total
2 delta-9 tetrahydrocannabinol concentration of not more than three-
3 tenths of one percent (0.3%) on a dry-weight basis after retesting,
4 and the option to remediate the industrial hemp through the
5 reasonable destruction of the flower or shredding of the entire lot
6 into a homogeneous biomass results in the remediation of any part of
7 the industrial hemp plant that is above three-tenths of one percent
8 (0.3%) on a dry-weight basis. All noncompliant hemp must be tracked
9 and documented. The State Board of Agriculture shall have
10 jurisdiction over such remediation, which includes, but is not
11 limited to, destruction through composting, burning, or other
12 regulated disposal methods if the industrial hemp is not remediated
13 into a final product before processing below three-tenths of one
14 percent (0.3%) on a dry-weight basis;
15 9. 11. “License” means authorization by the Department for any
16 person to grow and cultivate industrial hemp on a registered land
17 area as part of the Oklahoma Industrial Hemp Program; and
18 10. 12. “Processing” means converting industrial hemp into a
19 marketable form, including the production of all derivatives,
20 extracts, cannabinoids, isomers, acids, salts, and salts of isomers;
21 provided, that such products qualify as hemp under this section and
22 federal law; and
23 13. “Total tetrahydrocannabinols” or “total THC” means the sum
24 of the delta-9 tetrahydrocannabinol concentration and the
Req. No. 17299 Page 7

1 tetr ahydrocannabinol acid concentration, as measured after
2 decarboxylation, plus any additional cannabinoids designated by the
3 Secretary of the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services as
4 having similar effects.
5 SECTION 3. It being immediately necessary for the preservation
6 of the public peace, health or safety, an emergency is hereby
7 declared to exist, by reason whereof this act shall take effect and
8 be in full force from and after its passage and approval.
